  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the difference between overhanging beam and cantilever beam?",
  "response": "The terms \"overhanging beam\" and \"cantilever beam\" refer to two different types of structural beams that are used in engineering and construction. Here are the key differences between them:\n\n### Overhanging Beam\n1. **Definition**: An overhanging beam is a beam that extends beyond its support on one or both ends. It has portions that are unsupported, which means that part of the beam projects outward from its supports.\n  \n2. **Support Conditions**: An overhanging beam is typically simply supported at one or more points, with at least one end extending beyond a support. This can mean supports at both ends while still having an overhang at either or both ends.\n\n3. **Load Distribution**: The load on an overhanging beam can include vertical loads acting on the beam and will influence the reactions at the supports, as well as the bending moments within the beam.\n\n4. **Applications**: Overhanging beams are commonly used in applications like balconies, awnings, and some types of bridge designs.\n\n### Cantilever Beam\n1. **Definition**: A cantilever beam is a beam that is fixed at one end and free at the other. The free end can carry loads, while the fixed end is anchored to a wall or another support, allowing the beam to protrude outwards.\n\n2. **Support Conditions**: A cantilever beam has a single fixed support at one end, with the other end extending freely into space. This setup creates significant bending moments at the fixed support due to the loads acting on the beam.\n\n3. **Load Distribution**: Loads on a cantilever beam lead to bending moments and shear forces, primarily concentrated near the fixed support where maximum stress occurs.\n\n4. **Applications**: Cantilever beams are often used in bridges, balconies, and deep overhangs where support cannot be provided at both ends.\n\n### Summary\n- **Overhanging Beam**: Supported at one or more points with portions extending beyond the support(s).\n- **Cantilever Beam**: Fixed at one end and free at the other, with loads causing moments concentrated at the fixed support.\n\nUnderstanding these distinctions is crucial for selecting the appropriate beam type for specific structural applications and load-bearing requirements.",
